  "text": "In P2P designs like Tarzan [CITATION_1] and MorphMix [CITATION_2] , all participants both generate traffic and relay traffic for others. These systems aim to conceal whether a given peer originated a request or just relayed it from another peer. While Tarzan and MorphMix use layered encryption as above, Crowds [CITATION_3] simply assumes an adversary who cannot observe the initiator: it uses no public-key encryption, so any node on a circuit can read users' traffic.",
